<tr>
<td width="900" align=left colspan="9" class="more_non_p" align="center">
The concept of wavelength is a subtle yet profound concept
for the nature of light.  While we understand the difference
between colors at a very young age, 
it is a much higher concept to appreciate that 
the only quantity that distinguishes radio waves from blue light
and X-rays is the wavelength of the light. <br><br>

To promote an understanding of wavelength, 
we have designed a tool that enables students to produce
light with an arbitrary wavelength.  The easiest
approach is to stretch/compress the wave with the mouse, which
increases/decreases the wavelength.  Altenatively, one can input
a value (and a unit). <br>
        <tr><td colspan="5">
<img src="images/spacer_10x30.gif" width="10" height="20" /></td>
        </tr>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<table width="930" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5">
<tr>
<td width="150" colspan="5" valign="middle" class="more_non_p">
As the wavelength is modified,
several aspects of the presentation change.  In the upper right
corner is a graphic which sets a reference point for the size
of the current wavelength.  The example at the top of the page
shows the flu virus which has a diameter of roughly 1000 Angstroms.
The example to the right shows an example of submm light.
</td>
